This paper is about the computational complexity of election systems, specifically Copeland voting and its parameterized version Copeland^alpha. The paper discusses various scenarios of control and bribery in elections and analyzes the resistance or vulnerability of Copeland^alpha to these scenarios. This topic falls under the area of computational social choice, which is a subfield of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and theoretical computer science (cs.DS, cs.LG). The paper also involves analyzing algorithms and complexity, which falls under the category of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper discusses game theory and mechanism design, which are subfields of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT).
